# Walkthrough: Phase 1 & 2 Modular Component Foundation

I have completed the Phase 1 and Phase 2 implementations, establishing the foundational infrastructure for the new generic components (Operations, Analyzers, Mappings, Views, GIS, Visualization) and the Generalized Mapping System without breaking any existing workflow or Source logic.

## 1. Phase 1: Core Abstract Systems
Inside `app/core/`, I created the abstract contracts that will unify execution and validation across all future extensions:
- **`component.py`**: Defines `BaseComponent` (`component_key`, `display_name`, `validate`, `execute`).
- **`context.py`**: Defines `ExecutionContext` representing exactly the scope that execution engines will be handed (`source`, `mapping`, `metadata`, `params`).
- **`result.py`**: Defines `ComponentResult`, standardizing the return structures of operations vs. visualizations vs. views.
- **`validation.py`**: Defines the rigorous `ValidationResult` payload.
- **`registry.py`**: Implements the plugin registration system (`ComponentRegistry`).
- **`lineage.py`**: Helper definitions to map structural history mutations natively back to parent operations.
- **`selectors.py`**: Created `select_source_dataframe`, a safe boundary layer fetching directly via the legacy `Source.fetch()` object.

## 2. Phase 2: Generalized Mapping System
Inside `app/mappings/`, I built out the semantic mapping registry that replaces hardcoded row/column operations:
- **`mapping_targets.py`**: Established the `MappingTarget` and `ResolvedMapping` structures. These enable tracking targets across granularities (`field`, `record`, `dataset`, `geometry`) and associating them with universal `roles` (like `spatial_y` or `administrative_boundary`).
- **`rules/concrete_rules.py`**: Created an extensible rule system. I implemented `RenameRule`, `SemanticRoleRule`, `GeometryRoleRule`, and `TypeRoleRule` to dynamically mutate targeting parameters.
- **`mapping_engine.py`**: Provides the `MappingEngine` capable of receiving a `BaseMapping` or a raw array of `BaseMappingRule`s, sequencing them, and returning a finalized `ResolvedMapping` catalog for subsequent pipelines to consume.

## 3. Integrated Test Suites
I established a real, deterministically verifiable test environment using tangible datasets:
1. Created `tests/fixtures/sources/` with structural CSV representations for `fire_occurrences.csv`, `landslides.csv`, and `population.csv`.
2. Created a suite of tests inside `tests/test_core/` that specifically map and resolve Phase 1 components back to the real dataset instances. 
3. Created a suite of tests inside `tests/test_mappings/` that apply structural rules and query the semantic engine against these same real CSV models.

> [!TIP]
> Run the core and mappings test suites using `python -m pytest tests/`!

> [!NOTE]
> The existing `Source` and legacy operations remain entirely untouched. This foundation guarantees forward compatibility so that future operation engines and analyzers can simply ingest a `ResolvedMapping` and execute with guaranteed semantic intelligence against any tabular `Source`.
